        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>July 22<hi rend="superscript">nd</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>My Father desires me to say that he is so much engaged with other subjects that he cannot attend to Drosera at present. He is much obliged for the specimens &amp; returns the box registered &amp; hopes that its contents will survive their double journey in safety.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> The production of buds from Drosera leaves is a well known phenomenon but my Father has forgotten the references to the subject. My asks me to say, that he regrets that the digestive power of the fluid in the virgin pitchers of Nepenthes<ref target="#foot.f3"/> was not tested with small cubes of white of egg; until this is done he doubts whether physiologists would admit the presence of the ferment. He desires me to thank you much for your kind desire to help him</p>
<p>Yours truly | Francis Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the letter from LawsonTait, 21 July [1875].</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10086.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Lawson Tait, 21 July [1875]</ref>. <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi>: sundew.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Nepenthes</hi>: the tropical pitcher-plant.</note>
        </div>        
            
